102.description: Explore complex Jetpack Compose AnimatedVisibility and Target Based animations to flip cards and make dialogs expand and contract.
102.title: Taking Jetpack Compose Animations to the Next Level

112.description: DevOps is a set of practices that combines software development (Dev) and IT operations (Ops) to shorten the systems development life cycle and provide continuous delivery with high quality. Google Cloud offers a wide range of services that can help you implement DevOps practices with your team or app. Learn how to take advantage of a bunch of tools on offer from Google and ship your software faster, and safer.
112.title: DevOps on Google Cloud in less than 30 minutes

103.description: An introduction to Backend for Frontend pattern and how we are trying to move to a better architecture using the same at Prezzee. The talk explains about the common problem that many organisations face when trying to move from monoliths to micro-services and how having BFFs could be helpful. I also talk about when not to use BFFs and can give a brief overview of how we might implement it in Google Cloud.
103.title: BFFs could be your new Best Friends Forever

113.description:
Many teams use 2008's Clean Code to teach general software engineering practice to the next generation of Android engineers. But some recent biting criticism of this text leads us to question its place in the canon.

If not Clean Code, then what? A Philosophy of Software Design is a modern primer born from Stanford's famous CS190 course. Let's explore the text's advice as it applies to decomposition into functions and classes in an Android app.

If you're interested in the pedagogy of software engineering, or if you're still learning the principles of software design yourself, this talk will give you a framework to write clean code without writing Clean Code.
113.title: A Philosophy of Android Software Design

104.description: When it comes to cloud, we often have deliverables and work scoped out, then find we're missing deadlines, holding up other teams, or experiencing scope creep due to unknown unknowns. Gwenny will take us through an overview of how to plan and scope non-functional requirements earlier in a cloud computing component or product's lifecycle to make our projects more successful, on time, and on budget.
104.title: Non Functional Requirements for Cloud Computing Projects

114.description:
Navigation is fundamental to how we build our Android applications. However, process death and configuration changes put interesting restrictions on what kinds of architectures we can use for navigation compared with other platforms. This often means we end up with:
a) Navigation that lacks strong typing, or navigation that's difficult to use in multi-module projects
b) Navigation logic that is difficult to test in isolation
c) Difficulties sharing data between screens
d) Uncertainty over which layer of the application is really in control of navigation

In this talk, I propose a different way of thinking about navigation on Android, and how navigation architecture should work in general. This approach is simple, scalable and testable.

We will:
* Recap abstract concepts of navigation on Android
* Understand where current navigation approaches struggle
* Explore a different approach to navigation
* Examine practical examples of this approach
114.title: The Garden Path: A different approach to navigation on Android

105.description: In this talk, we will cover what foundation AI models are, and the different modalities that they cover. We will also discuss what Responsible AI is and what it means for developers. Lastly, we will talk about what Google is doing towards Responsible AI development internally and externally.
105.title: Foundation Models and Responsible AI

115.description:
From the early days of static HTML pages to the dynamic and interactive web applications of today, web development has come a long way. But what does the future hold for this ever-evolving field?

In this talk we will explore the latest trends, tools, and techniques employed by web developers to create immersive and engaging user experiences. From the adoption of progressive web apps (PWA) to project Fugu and the increasing importance of mobile optimization to the rise of front-end frameworks and the growing focus on accessibility and inclusivity, we will examine the key factors driving the evolution of web development in the present era.

Whether you are a seasoned web developer, decision maker, a tech enthusiast, or someone simply curious about the future of the digital realm, this session promises to provide valuable insights and ignite stimulating discussions. Join us as we unravel the possibilities and opportunities that lie ahead in the dynamic world of web development.
115.title: The Future of Web Development

106.description:
How to get started with AI/ML on Google Cloud and how models can be rapidly prototyped and brought to production with robust governance.

This will talk will also cover Gen AI Capability overview on Vertex AI.
106.title: AI/ML and Vertex AI

1062.description: Explore 'Designing the Future: Exploring AI's Impact on Software Design and UX.' This talk covers various aspects of AI's role in software design and user experience. Uncover how AI transforms design collaboration, enhances accessibility, shapes emerging trends, and promotes a human-centered approach. Plus, discover the new career opportunities AI brings to designers
1062.title: Designing the Future: Exploring AI's Impact on Software Design and UX

116.description: Konstantin recently led a team to roll out a new system that operates Auckland's electricity network. Here he takes us through the journey: applying development principles to operational problems, negotiating the right type and level of SLOs, working with tech and non-tech stakeholders to build trust, building a culture of continuous improvement, retrofitting automation onto existing systems, and picking the right type of compromises.
116.title: Engineering reliability critical infrastructure

117.description: If you aren't doing it, you are toast.
117.title: Coding with an AI Assistant

108.description:
Curious about career advancement in software engineering but not keen on the management track? Discover an alternative path: Staff Engineering.

This talk demystifies what it means to be a Staff-level Engineer and how this diverges from traditional Engineering Management roles. The session also offers a firsthand look at the oscillation between engineering and management roles, providing valuable insights for crafting a unique and fulfilling career trajectory.
108.title: Staff Engineering - A Technical Alternative to Management

1082.description: Summer of Tech is a non-profit organisation working to empower Aotearoa’s tech students and graduates with the help of our industry volunteers. We make it easy for employers to hire junior talent with our purpose-built platform, recruitment events and supportive team. Help us build a bright tech future for Aotearoa and register as an employer at www.summeroftech.co.nz.
1082.title: Empowering the next generation of tech superstars

118.description:
The ANZ Plus has one of the largest mobile teams in the southern hemisphere. As a team we are responsible for the app behind Australia’s fastest growing new digital bank. We also aim to have Zero tech debt - a goal we will never reach!

Why have a goal you will never reach? And why are we setting our sights on having none? Isn’t some level acceptable - or even desirable?

During this talk we will investigate the nature of tech debt. We will make the case that the ideal amount of tech debt is “zero” and look at how we can balance off this principal with the need to be incrementally improving and delivering rapidly.
118.title: Zero Technical Debt

119.description: In the world of constant change, discover how to futureproof your journey toward success. You will discover what superpowers you have,  and how to apply them best. What skills are most useful for empowering you to prosper,  both soft and hard. You will also be able to build your own holistic approach. Your success story starts here! Let's start it together.
119.title: Futureproofing for Success

120.title: Building your tech career with developer communities

132.description: Get your badge, coffee, enjoy talking meeting new people and getting ready for the day!
132.title: Registration & morning Coffee

137.title: Afterparty & Networking

annie-vella.bio: Annie is a lifelong computer enthusiast with two decades of experience in software engineering and technical leadership, having honed her craft across various industries in four countries. She has recently returned to an engineering role after her second stint in engineering management, now holding the title of Distinguished Engineer at Westpac NZ. She enjoys designing resilient systems, unearthing opportunities across the organization, and driving process improvements while emphasizing quality from the outset. Passionate about cultivating a culture of curiosity and continuous learning, Annie inspires engineers to work smarter, not harder, fostering an environment where technical brilliance thrives.
annie-vella.name: Annie Vella
annie-vella.title: Distinguished Engineer

katie-barnett.bio: Katie is passionate about all things Android. She has taken on a wide variety of challenging projects including in the live event, media and travel space. Her favourite thing is to see someone having a delightful experience using something she has worked on. Katie is very active in the development community, she is one of the organisers of GDG Melbourne and is a Women Techmakers Ambassador. She frequently runs events, speaks on technical and non-technical topics and enjoys writing blog posts to share her experience with others. Katie is based in Melbourne, Australia but loves to travel the world and outside of tech she enjoys boardgaming and attempting to finish many craft projects.
katie-barnett.name: Katie Barnett
katie-barnett.title: Team Lead

kate-nesmyelova.bio: Experienced IT leader with 20 years career across diverse domains, from banking to healthcare and more. Adept at crafting high-performing teams, streamlining processes, and delivering top-notch engineering solutions. Recognized for expertise in quality engineering, agile testing, coaching and mentoring teams to foster a culture of continuous learning and success.
kate-nesmyelova.name: Kate Nesmyelova
kate-nesmyelova.title: Quality Engineering

anna-cupples.bio: Anna has been working in the tech industry for 20 years, after studying computer science and information systems at Auckland University.  She has worked at iconic Kiwi companies such as Orion Health, Air New Zealand and is currently Head of Engineering at Trade Me.  She is passionate about tech, creating great products and growing individuals and teams.
anna-cupples.name: Anna Cupples
anna-cupples.title: Head of Engineering - Classifieds

jason-vella.bio: Jason is a highly skilled software professional with nearly two decades of experience and has a history of leading teams to design and build large distributed systems with an emphasis on elegant, scalable and robust solutions.
jason-vella.name: Jason Vella

oscar-wahltinez.bio: Oscar has over 10 years of industry experience, including leading engineering teams at Google and deploying software to billions of users as part of Windows and Android. He's also experienced in technical outreach and partnerships, responsible AI development, and foundation models as part of the Responsible AI team at Google.
oscar-wahltinez.name: Oscar Wahltinez
oscar-wahltinez.title: Developer Relations Engineer in Responsible AI at Google Research

aliaksei-kuncevic.bio: With over 15 years of experience in the tech industry, Lex is a Google Developer Expert and a Director and Founder of Angular Consulting, a company that provides IT services and solutions based on the Angular framework.
aliaksei-kuncevic.name: Aliaksei (Lex) Kuncevič
aliaksei-kuncevic.title: Founder

luke-sleeman.bio: Luke is a Principal Developer at Itty Bitty Apps specialising in Android app development. He's passionate about building inclusive, diverse and high performing teams.
luke-sleeman.name: Luke Sleeman
luke-sleeman.title: Android Principal

kristine-song.bio: Kristine started her Google journey in 2016 as an Administrative Business Partner to the director of Engineering and moved to the People & Operation team as a Software engineer recruiter. She is currently working as a regional lead for KR and ANZ sub-region leading the startup accelerator program and supporting developer communities.
kristine-song.name: Kristine Song
kristine-song.title: Regional Lead for KR and ANZ, Developer Ecosystem team

nakul-gowdra.bio:
Nakul is the lead for digital native customers and initiatives in New Zealand. He works closely with stakeholders to enable data driven outcomes and help them explore the best way to grow, whether via marketing analytics, research or sustainability.

With over a decade of experience in data analytics, Nakul facilitates deeper understanding of how Google’s data and AI tools can improve business and personal outcomes while upholding Google’s AI ethical principles.
nakul-gowdra.name: Nakul Gowdra
nakul-gowdra.title: Lead - Technologist (Digial Natives)

jk-gunnink.bio:
Hey there! I'm JK Gunnink, a software and cloud engineer with a passion for bringing rigor and operational efficiency to engineering teams. I'm a serverless specialist and harbinger of DevOps, and I love to bake in security practices along the way.

I really love building things, be it software, cloud infrastructure, helping to augment software teams to be elite performers or build out scalable and secure platforms. As a technical leader, I enjoy helping and uplifting capabilities from all I interact with and keep my tools sharp by attending conferences and experimenting with numerous side projects. In my day to day I love helping my team and my customers build and operate reliable, scalable, and secure software and platforms.
jk-gunnink.name: JK Gunnink
jk-gunnink.title: Engineering Lead

yekti-crow.bio:
Yekti Crow (she/her) is a Community Builder and Advocate for Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion in the workplace, currently working as the Industry Engagement Manager at Summer of Tech. With a decade working in government relations, international relations, global consulting, and non-profit, Yekti has a passion for fostering diverse and inclusive professional communities. She has worked across seven countries in Asia, the Americas, and her home in New Zealand.

Yekti's commitment to community empowerment is evident through her involvement with GLAM (LGBTQIA+ employee group) at McKinsey & Company, where she played an active role in championing inclusivity. Additionally, she actively contributes to the advancement of women by participating in initiatives like Jakarta's Women's March and, more recently, completing the Women of Colour Leadership Programme in Tāmaki Makaurau alongside other wāhine leaders. Yekti's work at Summer of Tech is devoted to breaking down barriers to entry for underrepresented individuals in the tech industry. Through paid internships and entry-level roles, Summer of Tech helps to connect opportunities for students and graduates while inspiring tech employers to build a supportive and inclusive Aotearoa tech industry.
yekti-crow.name: Yekti Crow
yekti-crow.title: Industry Engagement Manager

isaac-udy.bio: Meet Isaac Udy, an Android engineer with nearly a decade of experience. During this time, he has worked in teams of all sizes and discovered a passion for improving the engineering effectiveness of organisations. In the past three years, he has contributed to platform and enablement teams at Xero and ANZ, where he's built developer tools, written architectural guidance, and spent a lot of time pair programming. Isaac's interests lie in topics such as navigation, architecture, testing, developer experience, and modularization. Don't hesitate to strike up a conversation with him; he's always eager to exchange insights and hear about your own endeavours!
isaac-udy.name: Isaac Udy
isaac-udy.title: Android Engineer
